    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_929230157" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/929230157" />
    <a title="Becky" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1376766-becky"><img alt="Becky" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1630514212p2/1376766.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/929230157?book_show_action=true">May 05, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Becky" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Becky" href="/user/show/1376766-becky">Becky</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1376766-becky?shelf=reviewed">reviewed</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1376766-becky?shelf=2015">2015</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1376766-becky?shelf=dystopias">dystopias</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1376766-becky?shelf=romance-y">romance-y</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer929230157" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3285752427154143047">Well then. That was unexpected. This book and I didn&apos;t communicate very well. By which I mean that every time I thought something about it, I was wrong. I thought that this would be a more straightforward dystopia, with the government monitoring and controlling the people through mind-control words... only it wasn&apos;t really that. But it is kinda... in the more super secret organization way. <br/><br/>And in the beginning, it felt very trope-y. Teenaged orphan is told that she may have special abilities and</span>
  <span id="freeText3285752427154143047" style="display:none">Well then. That was unexpected. This book and I didn't communicate very well. By which I mean that every time I thought something about it, I was wrong. I thought that this would be a more straightforward dystopia, with the government monitoring and controlling the people through mind-control words... only it wasn't really that. But it is kinda... in the more super secret organization way. <br /><br />And in the beginning, it felt very trope-y. Teenaged orphan is told that she may have special abilities and is carted off to the school of [insert magic thing here] where she will learn what said magic thing is (in time) and how to use it. <br /><br />Only... then it suddenly wasn't really that anymore, either. <br /><br />I was surprised at the concept of this book - that there are words that can control people. It's like MAGIC! Or it is like backdoor hacker technology, if one takes the view that the brain is like a biological computer, as this book does. It's interesting, and detailed, and I loved the word-nerdiness in it quite a lot. <br /><br />But as far as the style, I don't know what to make of this book. It's non-linear, a jumbled confusion of timeline narratives... only it's not really all that confusing. Though that's not to say that it wouldn't have benefited from some sort of delineation. But part of the thriller feel stems from the reader not knowing when things are happening, and feeling that the things are happening now, in real time, only to find out in the next section that they were seeing a little bit of the past. It's confusing at the time, but it comes together and works. <br /><br />Or maybe <i>ywassey unter byloid keft</i> you just think it does. ;) </span>
  <a data-text-id="3285752427154143047" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


